[[File:Erica-2014-hr-2.jpg|thumb|'''Erica Meier'''|alt=]]
'''Erica Meier''' is the Executive Director of [[Compassion Over Killing]] (COK).

==Work with Compassion Over Killing==

Meier became [[Compassion Over Killing]]'s Executive Director in 2005, following five years as a volunteer. She has led the [[Animal rights movement|animal advocacy]] organization through several successful campaigns, including [http://cok.net/camp/victories/animal-care-certified-eggs-exposed/ ending the egg industry's use of "Animal Care Certified" claims] that could mislead consumers, as well as persuading companies like Dunkin’ Donuts<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dunkindonuts.com/DDBlog/2014/09/you_ve_asked_andwe.html#sthash.ys7Vymlv.dpbs|title=You’ve Asked and We’ve Heard: Almond Milk is Now at Dunkin’! « Dunkin' Donuts Blog|website=DunkinDonuts.com|access-date=2016-05-13}}</ref> and Subway<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://cok.net/blog/2015/06/1000-subways-vegan-menu/|title=1,000+ Subways Now Offer Vegan Menu!|last=www.cok.net|first=Compassion Over Killing {{!}}|date=2015-06-18|website=Compassion Over Killing|language=en-US|access-date=2016-05-13}}</ref> to offer vegan options.

COK's work is focused on the protection of farmed animals, and the organization has become best known for its investigations into the conditions facing [[intensive animal farming|animals on factory farms]]. Meier has been interviewed about this investigative work by major news outlets including [[CNN]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://eatocracy.cnn.com/2014/06/25/undercover-animal-abuse-videos/ |title=Undercover animal abuse videos could soon be outlawed |website=CNN |access-date=2016-03-29 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160402091527/http://eatocracy.cnn.com/2014/06/25/undercover-animal-abuse-videos/ |archivedate=2016-04-02 |df= }}</ref> [[Nightline|ABC's Nightline]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Blotter/plant-closed-usda-supplied-beef-burger/story?id=17051866|title=Plant Closed by USDA Supplied Beef for In-N-Out Burger|date=2012-08-22|publisher=ABC News|access-date=2016-05-13}}</ref> [[Associated Press]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.twincities.com/2015/11/12/undercover-video-shows-extreme-suffering-at-minnesota-hormel-supplier/|title=Undercover video shows ‘extreme suffering’ at Minnesota Hormel supplier – Twin Cities|last=Press|first=Pioneer|access-date=2016-03-29}}</ref> the [[Los Angeles Times]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/business/la-fi-animal-abuse-turkeys-20150622-story.html|title=Undercover video sheds light on turkey slaughter|website=latimes.com|access-date=2016-03-29}}</ref> and [[Reuters]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.yahoo.com/usda-probes-animal-abuse-video-hormel-pork-supplier-022818514.html|title=USDA probes animal abuse video at Hormel pork supplier QPP|website=Yahoo News|access-date=2016-03-29}}</ref>

In 2013, she was inducted into the [[Animal Rights Hall of Fame]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.arconference.org/hall-of-fame.htm|title=U.S. Animal Rights Hall of Fame|last=|first=|date=|website=Animal Rights National Conference|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref> Meier has delivered speeches at influential events including the [[Animal Rights National Conference]],<ref>{{Citation|last=Farm Animal Rights Movement|title=Erica Meier - Effective Tactics for Farmed Animals - Animal Rights National Conference 2015 AR2015|date=2016-01-28|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=q44p9LRlsV8&feature=youtu.be|accessdate=2016-05-13}}</ref> Maryland Animal Law Symposium, Forum on Industrial Animal Farming<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://today.law.harvard.edu/meat-eat-hls-hosts-forum-industrial-animal-farming-video/|title=The Meat We Eat: HLS hosts a forum on industrial animal farming (video) - Harvard Law Today|website=Harvard Law Today|access-date=2016-05-13}}</ref> hosted by the Harvard Food Law & Policy Clinic, the National Conference to End Factory Farming, and VegFests around the country.

Meier provided information used in the writing of the book ''[[Striking at the Roots|Striking at the Roots: A Practical Guide to Animal Activism]]'' (2008) by [[Mark Hawthorne (author)|Mark Hawthorne]] and was also interviewed in the documentary film “[[Speciesism: The Movie]]” (2013) by Mark Devries.

==Work in animal protection==

Erica has been [[Veganism|vegan]] for more than 20 years. Prior to starting at Compassion Over Killing, she served as an animal control officer in Washington, D.C., rescuing animals and enforcing anti-cruelty laws with the Washington Humane Society.

